# JavaScript - Coercion and falsy values 

## Falsy values

```javascript
undefined // variable without value
null //empty
0    //zero
NaN //not a number
"
```

```javascript
var user = "null";
var user = null;

if (user) { //if user is not null, then it is true
    console.log("condition is true");
}
```
*Any other values === truthy values*

## Coercion

```javascript
let user = "2";

console.log("2" + 2); //22, javascript doesnt know how to add a string and a number
console.log(2 + 2); //4
console.log(2 - "2"); //0, javascript knows how to subtract a string from a number

if (2 = user) { //loosly equal to two, so the code will actually run 
    console.log("condition is true");
}
if (2 === user) { //strictly equal to two, so the code will actually run 
    console.log("condition is true");
}
```
